currentStaff.profile: Ros started her working life as a primary school teacher, but was later lured into the world of archaeology, working for the Milton Keynes Archaeology Unit on excavations and as finds supervisor. Following this she worked on several sites as part of the Essex County Council Field Archaeology Unit. Her specialist interests are textile related objects and needlework tools. Ros joined the scheme in 2003.

Anna specialised in Anglo-Saxon archaeology at Cambridge, and later completed a Masters degree in Museum Studies at Leicester. Anna has since worked on several archaeological sites and in museums throughout the world! She is interested in Bronze Age metalwork, but has a special passion for Anglo-Saxon jewellery.

currentStaff.address_1: Department of Archaeology, College of Humanities, University of Exeter
currentStaff.profile: To follow shortly.

currentStaff.address_1: Bristol City Museum, Queens Road, Bristol
currentStaff.profile: Kurt has been working as the Finds Liaison Officer for North Lincolnshire for the past year and a half. Before this Kurt studied archaeology at the University of Cardiff . After graduating he worked as a field archaeologist for a number of units mainly around the south-west before undertaking a Masters degree at the University of Bristol . His main interests are the centuries before and after the Norman Conquest.

currentStaff.address_1: Ludlow Library and Museum Resource Centre
currentStaff.profile:
Peter has worked for the PAS as an FLO since 2003. He studied archaeology and history at the University of Wales , Bangor and also has a Master's degree in Landscape Archaeology from the University of Sheffield. Peter's career has been varied working in Wales , Ireland , and south-east England as a field archaeologist, exhibition officer, and as an assistant archaeological advisor. Peter has recently been accepted by the Institute of Archaeologists as a member (MIfA) their highest grade of membership. This is awarded to those with the greatest level of responsibility and competence within the Historic Environment sector.

Peter's main area of interest is the Bronze Age and later prehistory, but he also has a passion for the archaeology and artefacts of the Anglo-Saxon period.

Follow Peter's Blog at: http://finds.org.uk/blogs/themarches/

Frank has worked as a field archaeologist and illustrator for the Isle of Wight archaeological service for many years now. Over the last 15 years, he has been working closely with local detectorists. Frank is particularly interested in the Bronze Age and in inter-tidal archaeology and co-manages the Isle of Wight\'s coastal archaeology. Prior to working for the PAS he was an Arhaeological Field Officer for the Archaeological Service of the Isle of Wight Council. During this time, good relationships were established with landowners and metal detectorists. Consequently, metal detected finds have been recorded in the Isle of Wight Sites and Monuments Record and Historic Environment Record since 1980.

currentStaff.address_1: Tullie House Museum & Art Gallery Trust
currentStaff.profile: Dot originates from Germany and completed her undergraduate studies at the Freie Universitaet Berlin in 1999. She then moved to England because she always felt more at home here rather than in Germany. In England, she decided to get her teeth into British Archaeology; since she comes from Northern Germany originally, it only felt too natural to follow the \'trails\' of her fore-bearers, the Anglo-Saxons, and move to England. Thus, between 1999-2001, she studied Anglo-Saxon metalwork during the Migration Period (AD375-520) at Oxford and completed an MSt and an MPhil. In 2015 she completed her PhD on British Early Iron Age socketed axes (800-600BC) at the University of Lancashire.

Wendy studied Archaeology and History at Trinity College, University of Wales, before going on to do a Masters degree in Post Excavation at Leicester University. She previously spent three years working for the Sites and Monuments Record (HER). Wendy is interested in all metalwork, but particularly Early Medieval material. She has an interest in 'Viking' period artefacts, especially as evidence for settlement in England. She is patiently waiting for a Viking hoard to be discovered in Leicestershire! Whilst working as an FLO she has developed her interest in coinage, particularly early hammered and (by default) Roman.

Dr Adam Daubney is the finds liaison officer for Lincolnshire. He studied for his undergraduate degree in Archaeology and Prehistory at Sheffield University, and his MA and PhD at Leicester University. After graduating Adam worked as a field archaeologist and then as Assistant Keeper of Archaeology at Lincoln Museum before joining the scheme in 2003. Adam's research interests are material culture, multi-period artefac scatters, landscapes, and Roman Britain. His thesis 'Portable Antiquities, Palimpsests, and Persistent Places' explores several of these themes. Adam is a Fellow of the Society of Antiquaries, London.

currentStaff.address_1: Department of Early London History, Museum of London
currentStaff.profile: Kate studied archaeology at the University of Southampton for her first degree and thereafter a Master's degree in Museum Studies at University College London. After university Kate worked on collections management for the Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, Cambridge , sorting through its collections of British and worldwide archaeology across all periods. Since 2002 she has also worked as Finds Assistant for the Cambridge Archaeology Unit, splitting her time between the museum and the archaeological unit.

currentStaff.address_1: Historic Environment Team, Dorset County Council
currentStaff.profile: Ciorstaidh has worked as the FLO for Somerset and Dorset since 1999. Previously she was a Finds Officer in Hertfordshire, an excavator in Bedfordshire and an archaeological Education Assistant in Essex. She studied Archaeology and Prehistory at Sheffield University and gained a PGCE at King Alfred's College, Winchester. She remains a prehistorian at heart but since working for the Portable Antiquities Scheme has learned almost to enjoy numismatics.......

currentStaff.address_1: WYAS Advisory Service, Registry of Deeds
currentStaff.profile: Amy developed her interest in archaeology during her college years in Somerset and then studied for her degree at the University of York. She was employed as a Demonstrating Archaeologist at the Archaeological Resource Centre, and after graduating she worked at the Yorkshire Museum and Malton Museum. She then joined the PAS as a FLO in 2006 and has recorded over 10,000 objects. Amy is interested in all aspects of archaeology.

David is the FLO for Surrey and east Berkshire. He has been involved with Surrey archaeology since the mid 1970s and has worked on many excavations and reports. His background is in graphic design, and then later in archaeological illustration. David is the author of several publications, including a classification of Late Saxon Stirrup-Strap Mounts. The latter would not have been possible without the help of many metal detector users.

currentStaff.address_1: Department for Archaeology & Numismatics, National Museums & Galleries of Wales
currentStaff.profile: Mark graduated from University College , Cardiff in 1992, and soon after began working with the Department of Archaeology & Numismatics, National Museums & Galleries of Wales as site supervisor and surveyor on various fieldwork projects ranging from Palaeolithic to Medieval sites. Later, he worked cataloguing the Neolithic and Later Prehistoric collections housed at the National Museum and developed research interests in Bronze Age metalwork and its deposition.

currentStaff.address_1: Worcester City Art Gallery and Museum
currentStaff.profile: Angie studied Archaeology and Prehistory at Sheffield . After gaining her degree she became a field archaeologist in the south west. Angie was one of the original Finds Liaison Officers appointed in 1997. Since then Angie has recorded thousands of finds for the Portable Antiquities Scheme, including coins, pottery, glass and metalwork from all ages.

Katie has been with the Scheme since 1999, working first as a volunteer with the Hampshire FLO and then as Norfolk Finds Liaison Officer till 2003, as the Wiltshire Finds Liaison Officer until November 2012 and now as the Hampshire Finds Liaison Officer. Prior to this she studied Classical Studies before undertaking a Masters degree in Classical Archaeology at Liverpool University. Katie is especially interested in Bronze Age metalwork.

currentStaff.address_1: Norfolk Historic Environment Service, Union House
currentStaff.profile: Erica studied archaeology at University College London. Her particular areas of interest whilst there were British Pre-history and Public Archaeology. Thereafter she worked for Worcestershire County Council Archaeological Unit as a Finds Assistant working mostly on Roman and Post-Medieval sites. She has worked for the PAS since 2003.

Anni grew up in South Oxfordshire and has always had an interest in archaeology, history and anthropology. Anni studied archaeology at the University of Liverpool, and spent 7 years in commercial field archaeology, running small to large field and desk-based projects and post-excavation assessment. Anni joined the PAS in 2008 and is interested in all periods and aspects of archaeology but especially landscape archaeology and artefacts in the landscape, specifically the use of metal detecting as a survey technique. Anni is a Member of the Institute for Archaeologists and has an MSc in Applied Landscape Archaeology from the University of Oxford.

currentStaff.address_1: Museum of Liverpool, Department of Archaeology,
Historic Environment Team, Growth & Economy, Cambridgeshire County Council,

currentStaff.profile:
Julie started work with the Scheme in Northamptonshire in October 2008. She has a BA(hons) in Archaeology from the University of Reading, and gained an MA in Artefact Studies from University College London in 2004.

Before becoming an FLO, she worked as Finds Manager from several large scale excavations across the world, including CatalHoyuk in Turkey, Carriacou in the West Indies, the Roman Town at Silchester, and the M74 project in Glasgow.

Julie is also the Post-Medieval finds representative and social media officer for the Finds Research Group (www.findsresearchgroup.com).

Notice for September 2015

Julie is currently on sick leave and is not able to respond to enquiries. Please can you resend your message to the Archives and Heritage Service at archivist@northamptonshire.gov.uk who will keep a record of all enquiries received and assess whether one of the other FLOs may be able to help.

Laura Burnett has been the Finds Liaison Officer for Somerset for four years, she previously did the same post in Sussex for three years and has also worked for the PAS specialist in medieval and post-medieval coins in Oxford. She has a wide experience of the types of finds reported to the PAS and enjoys the variety of material that is brought in.

Laura was brought up on Exmoor and studied archaeology at Cambridge University then worked in Ireland, excavating sites about to be affected by road building, before returning to England to work at the National Monument Record in Swindon. In 2004 she went to UCL in London to do a Masters degree in Artefact Studies during which she spent some time with the Finds Liaison Officer in Suffolk. She then went on to work in Oxford and spent some time doing non-archaeological research in Devon before moving to Sussex to take up the FLO post there.

Laura is interested in artefacts of all periods but has a special interest in coins. She would be very interested to hear from anyone who has found items they would like identified and recorded. She is based in the Somerset Heritage Centre in Taunton and does regular finds days at Wells Museum, the Museum of Somerset and CHAC, Yeovil. For further details about the scheme or to arrange an appointment she can be contacted on 01823 347457, or by email: finds@swheritage.org.uk

Stephanie Smith is theFinds Liaison Officer for Sussex and works for the Sussex Archaeological Society.She has two MA postgraduate degrees: one in Artefact Studies from University College London's Institute of Archaeology and another in Classical Art & Archaeology from the University of Colorado at Boulder. Recently, Stephanie celebrated four years as Finds Liaison Officer and counts herself lucky to have so many wonderful finders and colleagues.
Stephanie grew up in the state of Michigan in the US. She has excavated at numerous sites, both in the US and abroad, including a Huron indigenous settlement site in Michigan, a Mesolithic prehistoric site in Yorkshire and an imperial villa complex in Rome.
Stephanie would love to hear from anyone who has found objects they would like to identify and record. She is located at the Barbican House Museum in Lewes, East Sussex and will be scheduling finds events in conjunction with multiple local museums throughout the year. For further details about the Portable Antiquities Scheme or to arrange an appointment you are welcome to contact her directly.

currentStaff.address_1: York Museums Trust, The Yorkshire Museum,

currentStaff.profile: Is the Finds Liaison Officer for Wiltshire. I Studied Ancient History and Archaeology in Lampeter and graduated in 2008. I have volunteered and worked for the PAS since 2006 all over the country including as the FLO (maternity cover) for Worcestershire and Warwickshire.

I've been working with finds since I finished my degree in 2002. Although on all university excavations, I tended to end up in the Finds Hut as opposed to out in the trenches with everyone else. Once I finished my degree, I started working for Cotswold Archaeology within their finds department. It was during my time there, that I gathered all the knowledge about the different types of pottery. Unfortunately due to the credit crunch, I was made redundant in June 2009. However this turned out to be very well timed, as I started working within the PAS West Midlands from August of that year. I left the West Midlands Team in March 2011 to cover Vanessa Oakden (Cheshire & Merseyside FLO)'s maternity leave, which was quite good fun and it made a nice change being a bit further north and seeing a different range of finds. Following that, I briefly went back into commercial archaeology as the Finds & Archives Officer for Wardell Armstrong Archaeology, based in Carlisle. However I never felt at home that far up north, so I couldn't wait to return back to the West Midlands PAS team.

I have worked with material from a wide variety of different sites and dates, from Neolithic collared urns and Bronze Age socketed axes to Iron Age log ladders (that required lifting from within their 6 foot deep pit) to Roman military finds out in Bulgaria to Post medieval urban deposits and finds.

I am more than happy to look at any pottery sherds or other 'eyes only' finds. Although I will admit that I am more fond of both Roman and medieval finds than pot sherds nowadays. At the moment I must admit I've got a particular interest in Medieval strap fittings, in particular the King's Head belt buckles / strap clasps.
To follow.

Ellie has both a BA and an Msc in Archaeology from the University of York. She began working with the Portable Antiquities Scheme in 2011 and has worked with various FLO's across the North. She is interested in Medieval to Post-Medieval coinage and the various forms of personal ornamentation.

Alastair has been the Finds Liaison Officer for Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire since May 2015. He studied Ancient History and Archaeology at the University of Bristol, before doing a master's degree in Egyptology. Alastair has been working for the PAS since May 2013, firstly as a volunteer for the FLO in Wiltshire. He then became the Finds Liaison Assistant for Wiltshire and Hampshire and then the Finds Recording Assistant for Lincolnshire. Before starting his current role, Alastair volunteered in the Department of Coins and Medals at the British Museum, where he worked through a hoard of more than 7000 Roman radiate coins. In spite of this, he is still fascinated by Roman coinage and other Roman finds, but is also very interested in seeing finds from other periods as well.

Alastair is normally based at Derby Museum and Art Gallery, but works in Nottingham twice a month. He works at Nottingham City Museums and Galleries at Brewhouse Yard, Castle Boulevard, Nottingham NG7 1FB on the first Wednesday of each month, and at The University of Nottingham Museum, Lakeside Arts Centre and Museum, University Park, Nottingham NG7 2RD on the third Tuesday of every month. If you would like to bring objects in on those days please email or telephone in advance to book an appointment.

Ben studied Archaeology and Anthropology at Cambridge University, specialising in Archaeology in the final two years. He completed a Master's in Artefact Studies at University College London in 2013, focusing on Prehistoric and Roman metalwork. Since then he has been a volunteer with the PAS in London, Headley Trust Intern (split between the PAS in London and Essex) and then Finds Liaison Assistant for Essex between January and June 2015. His areas of interest are Iron Age decorative metalwork and Roman small finds.
